---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const title = "Insurance for International Architects | Compare Expat Plans";
const description = "Health insurance guide for Architects working internationally, covering architectural design positions abroad, building design careers, and global architecture opportunities.";
const headline = "Insurance for International Architects";
const subheadline = "Coverage solutions for Architects working abroad, designing buildings internationally, and pursuing careers across architectural firms, development companies, and design practices worldwide.";
const canonicalPath = "/guides/architect-insurance";
const heroBackgroundImage = "/images/guides/architect-insurance-hero.png";

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', label: 'Overview' },
  { id: 'coverage-needs', label: 'Coverage Needs' },
  { id: 'work-settings', label: 'Work Settings' },
  { id: 'credentials', label: 'Credentials' },
  { id: 'occupational-health', label: 'Occupational Health' },
  { id: 'work-demands', label: 'Work Demands' },
  { id: 'career-considerations', label: 'Career Considerations' },
  { id: 'faqs', label: 'FAQs' },
  { id: 'next-steps', label: 'Next Steps' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title={title}
  description={description}
  headline={headline}
  subheadline={subheadline}
  canonicalPath={canonicalPath}
  heroBackgroundImage={heroBackgroundImage}
  tocItems={tocItems}
>
  <article class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">

    <section id="overview">
      <h2>International Architect Careers</h2>
      <p>
        Architects design buildings and structures, creating functional and aesthetic spaces that shape how people live, work, and interact. International architecture offers opportunities to design landmark projects worldwide, work with diverse clients and contexts, and shape built environments across cultures.
      </p>
      <p>
        International architecture opportunities exist through global architectural firms, development companies, government projects, and design practices with international portfolios.
      </p>
      <p>
        This guide addresses insurance considerations for Architects working abroad across architectural firms, development companies, and design practices worldwide.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="coverage-needs">
      <h2>Coverage Needs for Architects</h2>

      <ComparisonTable
        columns={[
          { key: 'need', header: 'Coverage Need' },
          { key: 'why', header: 'Why It Matters' },
          { key: 'typical', header: 'Coverage Situation?' },
        ]}
        rows={[
          { need: 'General health coverage', why: 'Professional health maintenance', typical: 'Usually employer-provided' },
          { need: 'Eye coverage', why: 'CAD and design software work', typical: 'Important for role' },
          { need: 'Ergonomic coverage', why: 'Extended design sessions', typical: 'Consider including' },
          { need: 'Travel coverage', why: 'Site visits and client meetings', typical: 'Essential for role' },
          { need: 'Physical coverage', why: 'Construction site visits', typical: 'Consider for role' },
          { need: 'Mental health support', why: 'Project deadlines and client pressure', typical: 'Consider including' },
        ]}
      />

      <h3>Design-Intensive Work</h3>
      <p>
        Architects spend extended hours with CAD software, 3D modeling, and detailed drawings. This precision design work creates significant eye strain. The detailed nature of architectural drawings requires sustained visual focus. Eye coverage supports long-term career sustainability in architecture.
      </p>
      <p>
        Design work also involves extended sessions at workstations. Ergonomic coverage supports sustained design productivity.
      </p>

      <h3>Site Visits and Construction Oversight</h3>
      <p>
        Architects regularly visit construction sites for inspections, client meetings, and design coordination. Site visits involve physical hazards—uneven terrain, construction equipment, and changing conditions. Physical and travel coverage supports the field components of architectural practice.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="work-settings">
      <h2>Coverage by Work Setting</h2>

      <h3>Large Firm</h3>
      <p>
        Global architecture firm. Comprehensive benefits. Major projects. Large firms offer scale and resources.
      </p>

      <h3>Mid-Size Firm</h3>
      <p>
        Regional architecture firm. Professional benefits. Diverse projects. Mid-size offers balance.
      </p>

      <h3>Small Practice</h3>
      <p>
        Boutique architecture studio. Benefits vary. Design focus. Small practices offer craft.
      </p>

      <h3>Corporate</h3>
      <p>
        In-house corporate architecture. Corporate benefits. Facility focus. Corporate offers stability.
      </p>

      <h3>Government</h3>
      <p>
        Public sector architecture. Government benefits. Public projects. Government offers security.
      </p>
    </section>

    <CTABox
      title="Coverage for Architects"
      description="Compare international health plans designed for Architects working abroad across architectural firms, development companies, and design practices worldwide."
      buttonText="Compare Architect Plans"
      buttonHref="/"
      variant="highlight"
    />

    <section id="credentials">
      <h2>Credentials and Professional Recognition</h2>

      <h3>Licensure</h3>
      <p>
        Professional architecture license. Country-specific requirements. Registration essential. Licensure required for practice.
      </p>

      <h3>Education</h3>
      <p>
        Architecture degree. Accredited program. Professional degree. Education required.
      </p>

      <h3>Portfolio</h3>
      <p>
        Design work samples. Built projects. Competition entries. Portfolio demonstrates capability.
      </p>

      <h3>Specialization</h3>
      <p>
        Building type expertise. Sustainability focus. Technical specialty. Specialization adds value.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="occupational-health">
      <h2>Occupational Health Considerations</h2>

      <h3>Eye Strain</h3>
      <p>
        CAD work. Detailed drawings. Screen time. Eye coverage important.
      </p>

      <h3>Site Hazards</h3>
      <p>
        Construction visits. Physical environment. Safety requirements. Physical coverage relevant.
      </p>

      <h3>Project Pressure</h3>
      <p>
        Design deadlines. Client expectations. Coordination demands. Mental health support valuable.
      </p>

      <h3>Travel Requirements</h3>
      <p>
        Site visits. Client meetings. International projects. Travel coverage essential.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="work-demands">
      <h2>Managing Work Demands</h2>

      <h3>Design</h3>
      <p>
        Conceptual design. Schematic development. Design refinement. Design creates vision.
      </p>

      <h3>Documentation</h3>
      <p>
        Construction documents. Technical drawings. Specifications. Documentation enables construction.
      </p>

      <h3>Coordination</h3>
      <p>
        Engineering coordination. Consultant management. Client communication. Coordination aligns teams.
      </p>

      <h3>Construction Administration</h3>
      <p>
        Site observation. Change management. Quality review. Administration ensures intent.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="career-considerations">
      <h2>Career Considerations</h2>

      <h3>Solid Demand</h3>
      <p>
        Building continues worldwide. Development ongoing. Design valued. Demand steady globally.
      </p>

      <h3>Career Paths</h3>
      <p>
        Project Architect. Associate. Partner. Principal. Own practice. Multiple paths.
      </p>

      <h3>Credential Portability</h3>
      <p>
        Design skills transfer. Licensure varies by country. Reciprocity agreements exist. Portfolio travels.
      </p>

      <h3>Field Evolution</h3>
      <p>
        Sustainability focus. BIM advancement. AI design tools. Field evolving continuously.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="faqs">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="space-y-6">
        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">I'm an architect considering international work. What should I know?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Firms provide benefits. Licensure varies by country. Portfolio essential. Design skills transfer well.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">Do employers provide international coverage?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Large firms yes. Global practices yes. Travel coverage common. Benefits typically good at major firms.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">Is eye strain a significant concern?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Yes for architects. CAD work intensive. Detailed drawings demanding. Eye coverage important.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">Do architecture credentials transfer internationally?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Design skills universal. Licensure varies by country. Reciprocity agreements help. Portfolio speaks globally.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">Are site visits common?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Yes typically. Construction observation required. Client sites visited. Travel coverage essential.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-0 mb-2">What's the career outlook?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
            Building continues globally. Sustainability driving demand. Design valued. Outlook positive.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="next-steps">
      <h2>Next Steps</h2>
      <p>
        Start by evaluating employer benefits packages. Prioritize eye coverage for design work. Ensure travel coverage for site visits. Verify international coverage scope for your practice locations.
      </p>
      <p>
        Architects shape built environments worldwide. Your coverage should support architecture careers—addressing design and site demands, covering health maintenance, and protecting you across architectural practice worldwide.
      </p>
    </section>

    <CTABox
      title="Protect Your Architecture Career"
      description="Compare international health plans designed for Architects working abroad across architectural firms, development companies, and design practices worldwide."
      buttonText="Compare Plans Now"
      buttonHref="/"
      variant="highlight"
    />

  </article>
</PageShell>
